english:
  title: A Preface to a Poem Sending Off Steward Yul
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Vice Director of the Imperial Stables, Minister Zhu, and the Ministry of War official, Minister Duanmu, came bearing the Son of Heaven's command to procure horses. Their retinue of ten men were all among the finest scholars of the National Academy. As their successive expeditions arrived, with each shipment numbering a thousand steeds, they divided and dispatched them in stages. This was the seventh such expedition. Steward Yul led them all forward on their journey. Minister Duanmu, reflecting that they had come together yet parted so soon, poured his wistful feelings into verses and, showing me undeserved honor, asked me to write this preface.

    Considering our small realm: ever since our Grand Progenitor founded his dominion over all lands, we were first to submit and become an eastern tributary. Envoys arrive some years annually, in other years biennially. Never have I witnessed so many capable and virtuous men in the retinue as in this present day. Steward Yul possesses a luminous countenance and commanding stature, his bearing dignified and solemn. His spirit is stern yet his face serene; his conduct austere yet his words gentle. One can discern both the excellence of his natural endowments and the refinement of his learning. A scholar of such accomplishment could excel in any station among the officials. Yet to send him thousands of leagues hence to procure horses—is this not an underutilization of his talents?

    Yet Steward Yul's daily study has been devoted to one model: Confucius himself. In antiquity, Confucius served as a charioteer; he also served as a keeper of granaries where livestock flourished. And our Eastern lands are where Confucius wished to dwell. So for a scholar to perform what Confucius once performed, to journey where Confucius desired to go—is this not also a blessing? When a scholar regards all affairs under heaven, questioning neither the rank of office nor the magnitude of task, but performs whatever rightly falls to him with equal dedication, then there is nothing he cannot embrace, and wherever he goes, he finds good fortune. Only thus can one undertake great responsibilities and achieve great deeds. That the Sage Emperor tests him in this matter surely presages that he shall entrust him with greater burdens hereafter. Therefore, Steward Yul, redouble your efforts!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Confucius served as a charioteer (executor/charioteer) for the Ji family and as keeper of the granaries in his youth.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'Eastern lands' reflects Korea's historical position as a tributary state and the author's pride in Korean culture as a center of Confucian learning.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The philosophical argument presented here reflects neo-Confucian thought: that a virtuous scholar should accept any role assigned by his sovereign, finding spiritual meaning in humble service.'
